│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe assertion in                                    │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() fires because the VPlan-based cost  │
│ model and the legacy cost model select different vectorization factors (VFs), │
│ and the fallback justification (planContainsAdditionalSimplifications)        │
│ returns false. This means the code believes there were no extra               │
│ simplifications in the chosen VPlan to justify the VF mismatch, so it         │
│ asserts. In the reproducer, the loop models an AnyOf reduction that the VPlan │
│ codegen optimizes by removing a select instruction used in the legacy cost    │
│ model's pattern recognition/costing.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash    │
│ occurs immediately at the assertion verifying cost model agreement. No other  │
│ transformations are performed beforehand. The disagreement is between         │
│ BestFactor.Width (from VPlan-based costing) and LegacyVF.Width (from          │
│ selectVectorizationFactor using the legacy cost model). The assertion         │
│ condition depends on planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(BestPlan, CostCtx, │
│ OrigLoop). For AnyOf reductions, the select instruction is removed in VPlan   │
│ codegen, but earlier in precomputeCosts the select is both costed and marked  │
│ as skipped (SkipCostComputation). Because it is skipped,                      │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications does not consider its absence a         │
│ simplification.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn precomputeCosts (lines         │
│ ~7212–7234), for AnyOf reductions, the legacy cost model pre-costs the select │
│ instruction and then inserts it into CostCtx.SkipCostComputation. Later,      │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications determines whether missing IR           │
│ instructions correspond to additional simplifications only if they are not    │
│ skipped. By marking the select as skipped, the mechanism that should          │
│ recognize the eliminated select as an additional simplification is disabled.  │
│ Consequently, the assertion sees a VF mismatch without permitted              │
│ justification and triggers. This is a logic interaction specific to AnyOf     │
│ reduction handling.\n\nTherefore, the root cause is: The AnyOf reduction      │
│ select instruction, which is intentionally removed by VPlan codegen, is       │
│ incorrectly added to SkipCostComputation, preventing                          │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications from recognizing its removal as a valid │
│ simplification to justify VF divergence.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit  │
│ lines 7227–7234 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp inside the │
│ AnyOf reduction handling block. Remove the insertion of the select into       │
│ CostCtx.SkipCostComputation and add a clarifying comment.\nOriginal           │
│ snippet:\n  assert(!CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.contains(Select) &&           │
│ \"reduction op visited multiple times\");\n                                   │
│ CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.insert(Select);\n  auto ReductionCost =           │
│ CostCtx.getLegacyCost(Select, VF);\n\nProposed change:\n                      │
│ assert(!CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.contains(Select) && \"reduction op        │
│ visited multiple times\");\n  // Do NOT mark the AnyOf select as skipped:     │
│ VPlan codegen may remove it.\n  // Leaving it unskipped allows                │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() to\n  // treat its absence as a       │
│ simplification, avoiding false assertion failures\n  // when the VPlan-based  │
│ and legacy cost models legitimately diverge.\n  auto ReductionCost =          │
│ CostCtx.getLegacyCost(Select, VF);\n\nThis preserves correct costing (the     │
│ legacy cost of the select is still added once) and enables detection of its   │
│ elimination as an additional simplification.\n\nWhy safe:\n- The select is    │
│ not represented by a VPlan recipe when eliminated, so Plan.cost(VF, CostCtx)  │
│ will not double-count it.\n- The second precomputeCosts call in computeBestVF │
│ uses a fresh CostCtx, so the cost is recomputed consistently.\n- The          │
│ assertion's justification path now returns true when the select is absent,    │
│ preventing the crash.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy not inserting the AnyOf select    │
│ into SkipCostComputation, we allow planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to   │
│ recognize its removal and justify VF discrepancies between the VPlan and      │
│ legacy cost models. This resolves the assertion failure without altering      │
│ underlying VF selection logic or cost semantics, and maintains correctness    │
│ for other reduction kinds.\n"})                                               │
