│ used in the legacy cost model's pattern recognition/costing.                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The crash occurs immediately at the assertion verifying cost model agreement. │
│ No other transformations are performed beforehand. The disagreement is        │
│ between BestFactor.Width (from VPlan-based costing) and LegacyVF.Width (from  │
│ selectVectorizationFactor using the legacy cost model). The assertion         │
│ condition depends on planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(BestPlan, CostCtx, │
│ OrigLoop). For AnyOf reductions, the select instruction is removed in VPlan   │
│ codegen, but earlier in precomputeCosts the select is both costed and marked  │
│ as skipped (SkipCostComputation). Because it is skipped,                      │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications does not consider its absence a         │
│ simplification.                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In precomputeCosts (lines ~7212–7234), for AnyOf reductions, the legacy cost  │
│ model pre-costs the select instruction and then inserts it into               │
│ CostCtx.SkipCostComputation. Later, planContainsAdditionalSimplifications     │
│ determines whether missing IR instructions correspond to additional           │
│ simplifications only if they are not skipped. By marking the select as        │
│ skipped, the mechanism that should recognize the eliminated select as an      │
│ additional simplification is disabled. Consequently, the assertion sees a VF  │
│ mismatch without permitted justification and triggers. This is a logic        │
│ interaction specific to AnyOf reduction handling.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ Therefore, the root cause is: The AnyOf reduction select instruction, which   │
│ is intentionally removed by VPlan codegen, is incorrectly added to            │
│ SkipCostComputation, preventing planContainsAdditionalSimplifications from    │
│ recognizing its removal as a valid simplification to justify VF divergence.   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 7227–7234 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp       │
│ inside the AnyOf reduction handling block. Remove the insertion of the select │
│ into CostCtx.SkipCostComputation and add a clarifying comment.                │
│ Original snippet:                                                             │
│   assert(!CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.contains(Select) && "reduction op       │
│ visited multiple times");                                                     │
│   CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.insert(Select);                                 │
│   auto ReductionCost = CostCtx.getLegacyCost(Select, VF);                     │
│                                                                               │
│ Proposed change:                                                              │
│   assert(!CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.contains(Select) && "reduction op       │
│ visited multiple times");                                                     │
│   // Do NOT mark the AnyOf select as skipped: VPlan codegen may remove it.    │
│   // Leaving it unskipped allows planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() to   │
│   // treat its absence as a simplification, avoiding false assertion failures │
│   // when the VPlan-based and legacy cost models legitimately diverge.        │
│   auto ReductionCost = CostCtx.getLegacyCost(Select, VF);                     │
│                                                                               │
│ This preserves correct costing (the legacy cost of the select is still added  │
│ once) and enables detection of its elimination as an additional               │
│ simplification.                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ Why safe:                                                                     │
│ - The select is not represented by a VPlan recipe when eliminated, so         │
│ Plan.cost(VF, CostCtx) will not double-count it.                              │
│ - The second precomputeCosts call in computeBestVF uses a fresh CostCtx, so   │
│ the cost is recomputed consistently.                                          │
│ - The assertion's justification path now returns true when the select is      │
│ absent, preventing the crash.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By not inserting the AnyOf select into SkipCostComputation, we allow          │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to recognize its removal and justify VF │
│ discrepancies between the VPlan and legacy cost models. This resolves the     │
│ assertion failure without altering underlying VF selection logic or cost      │
│ semantics, and maintains correctness for other reduction kinds.               │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
